<FlowDocument xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
              xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
              Foreground="#E0E0E0"
              Background="#1E1F22"
              FontFamily="Segoe UI"
              FontSize="14"
              PagePadding="32,24,32,24">

    <Paragraph FontSize="28" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Create NPC / Create Enemy and Adjust NPC / Adjust Enemy Event Points
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#A0A0A0" FontSize="13" Margin="0,0,0,16">
        How to spawn police, enemies, civilians, and other NPCs, and how to later alter an existing NPC using Adjust NPC / Adjust Enemy.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,0,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,4,0,4">
        Create NPC / Create Enemy Overview
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The <Bold>Create NPC</Bold> or <Bold>Create Enemy</Bold> Event Point spawns a non-playable
        character into the mission. This includes extra police, enemies, citizens, gang members,
        named characters, and other human actors.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        NPC Event Points are common in mission files and should be organised clearly. Good grouping
        makes it much easier to inspect the mission later, especially once the file contains hundreds
        of Event Points.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_npc_overview.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A2F3A" BorderBrush="#4A5A7A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#AFC8FF">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Related but different Event Point:</Run>
                <Run>
                    Create NPC / Create Enemy spawns a new character.
                    Adjust NPC / Adjust Enemy does not spawn a new character; it targets an already-created NPC and changes that NPC later.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Suggested Grouping
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The common properties are the same as other Event Points: index, type, letter group, colour,
        position, trigger settings, and listening mode. For NPCs, it is useful to create your own
        grouping convention.
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Group C / Blue</Bold> — police officers.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Group C / Red</Bold> — enemies or hostile gang members.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Group C / White</Bold> — civilians.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        This is only a recommended convention. You can use whatever colours and letters make sense
        for your mission.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_npc_grouping_example.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Example: Adding Two Police Officers
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        In this example, two police officers are added in <Bold>Group C</Bold> with the colour
        <Bold>Blue</Bold>.
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Click <Bold>Add</Bold> in the Event Points panel.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Select <Bold>Create NPC</Bold> or <Bold>Create Enemy</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set the letter group to <Bold>C</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set the colour to <Bold>Blue</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set the NPC type to <Bold>Cop</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Place the first police officer on the map.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Select the created officer and press <Bold>Ctrl+C</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Move the cursor to the desired second position and press <Bold>Ctrl+V</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Rotate each officer using the orange direction handle so they face the intended target, such as a Baalrog.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Copying and pasting an Event Point preserves the colour and letter grouping. This makes it
        faster to duplicate similar NPCs without repeatedly setting their group data.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_npc_two_cops_example.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Editing NPC Spawn Properties
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Double-click an NPC Event Point to edit it. The type-specific properties determine who the
        NPC is, how much health they have, how they move, what AI behaviour they use, what weapons
        they carry, and what item they may drop when searched.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_npc_edit_window.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        NPC Type
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The <Bold>Type</Bold> field controls what kind of character is spawned. Available types
        include civilians, police, gang members, named characters, and variations with starting
        weapons.
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Civilian</Bold> and <Bold>Civilian With Balloon</Bold> — these appear to behave the same.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Woman</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Fat Woman</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Workman with Green Overalls</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Black Gang Member</Bold> — clothing colour can change depending on the Event Point number.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>White Gang Member</Bold> variants, including Bish and McClean.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Gordansky</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Old Man in Leather Jacket</Bold> / Wild Bill.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>MIB</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Darci</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Roper</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Various versions of these types with starting weapons.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Count
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The <Bold>Count</Bold> field is available for editing, but testing suggests that only one
        NPC spawns per Event Point regardless of the count entered. To spawn multiple NPCs, create
        or copy multiple Event Points.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Health
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The <Bold>Health</Bold> value controls the amount of health the NPC has.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Starting Weapons
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Starting Weapons define the weapons that the NPC has in their possession when spawned.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Item Drops
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Item Drops define what can be found when the NPC is searched after being arrested or killed.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#3A2A2A" BorderBrush="#7A4A4A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#E0A0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Important:</Run>
                <Run>
                    NPC Count appears editable but generally only one character spawns per Event Point.
                    Use copy/paste for multiple NPCs.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#666" Margin="0,18,0,14"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="26" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Adjust NPC / Adjust Enemy Event Point
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>Adjust NPC</Bold> or <Bold>Adjust Enemy</Bold> is a separate Event Point type, but it
        is closely related to <Bold>Create NPC / Create Enemy</Bold>. Instead of spawning a new
        character, it modifies an NPC that already exists in the mission.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        This is useful when you want an NPC’s behaviour to change during the mission. For example,
        an NPC can start by standing still, then later be adjusted to follow the player, patrol
        waypoints, flee, attack, wander, or use different AI behaviour.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#4A2424" BorderBrush="#C45A5A" BorderThickness="2"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="14">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#FFD0D0" FontSize="15">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Critical required field:</Run>
                <Run>
                    Adjust NPC / Adjust Enemy must have Target EP set. Target EP is not optional.
                    Target EP must be the Event Point number of the existing NPC that you want to change.
                    For example, if the NPC you want to modify is Event Point 12, set Target EP to 12.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_adjust_npc_overview.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Target EP: The NPC Being Adjusted
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The <Bold>Target EP</Bold> parameter tells the game which existing NPC Event Point should be
        modified. This value must correspond to the <Bold>Event Point number</Bold> of a previously
        created NPC.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        For example, if you created a police officer and that police officer appears in the Event
        Points list as <Bold>Event Point 12</Bold>, then an Adjust NPC / Adjust Enemy Event Point
        that modifies that officer must have:
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Border Background="#25272B" BorderBrush="#444" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="10">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#E0E0E0" FontFamily="Consolas">
Target EP = 12
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph>
        The Target EP does <Bold>not</Bold> mean the Adjust NPC Event Point’s own index number. It
        means the index number of the NPC being changed.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        If Target EP points to the wrong Event Point, the wrong NPC may be adjusted, or the event may
        appear to do nothing. If Target EP is blank, zero, or not set to a valid NPC Event Point, the
        adjustment will not correctly target the intended character.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_adjust_npc_target_ep.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A2F3A" BorderBrush="#4A5A7A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#AFC8FF">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Think of it this way:</Run>
                <Run>
                    Create NPC makes the character. Adjust NPC points to that character by Event Point number and changes it later.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Adjust NPC Can Have Its Own Trigger
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Because Adjust NPC / Adjust Enemy is its own Event Point, it can have its own separate
        trigger condition. This means the adjustment does not need to happen immediately. It can be
        triggered later by mission logic.
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Dependency</Bold> — adjust the NPC after another Event Point has completed.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Player Enters Radius</Bold> — adjust the NPC when the player reaches an area.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Conversation Finished</Bold> — adjust the NPC after dialogue completes.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Counter Reaches Value</Bold> — adjust the NPC after mission progress reaches a certain value.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Timer</Bold> — adjust the NPC after a delay.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        This makes Adjust NPC useful for mission scripting. A character can begin passive, then later
        become hostile, follow a path, flee, guard something, or change movement mode based on the
        mission state.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Example: Change an NPC from Stand Still to Follow
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        This example shows the intended relationship between Create NPC and Adjust NPC:
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Create an NPC using <Bold>Create NPC / Create Enemy</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set the NPC’s initial movement to <Bold>Stand Still</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Place the NPC on the map and click <Bold>OK</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Look at the Event Points list and note the NPC’s Event Point number. For example, the NPC might be <Bold>Event Point 12</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Add a new Event Point and choose <Bold>Adjust NPC</Bold> or <Bold>Adjust Enemy</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set <Bold>Target EP</Bold> to <Bold>12</Bold>, because Event Point 12 is the NPC being modified.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set the new movement type, for example <Bold>Follow</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>If Follow needs a target, set <Bold>Follow EP</Bold> to the Event Point number to follow, such as the Player Event Point.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set the trigger for when the adjustment should occur, such as <Bold>Player Enters Radius</Bold> or <Bold>Dependency</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Save and test the mission.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#3A2A2A" BorderBrush="#7A4A4A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#E0A0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Common mistake:</Run>
                <Run>
                    Do not put the Adjust NPC Event Point’s own number into Target EP unless the Adjust NPC event is also somehow the NPC,
                    which it normally is not. Target EP should be the Event Point number of the NPC created by Create NPC / Create Enemy.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Basic Adjust NPC / Adjust Enemy Workflow
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Create the NPC using <Bold>Create NPC / Create Enemy</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Note the created NPC’s <Bold>Event Point number</Bold> from the Event Points list.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Add a new Event Point and select <Bold>Adjust NPC</Bold> or <Bold>Adjust Enemy</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set <Bold>Target EP</Bold> to the Event Point number of the NPC you want to modify.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Change the desired NPC properties, such as movement, AI behaviour, flags, or related fields.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set the trigger for when the adjustment should happen.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Save and test the mission to confirm the correct NPC changes at the correct time.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#666" Margin="0,18,0,14"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

<Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Movement, AI Types, and Flags Reference
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#A0A0A0" FontSize="13" Margin="0,0,0,16">
        Reference for Create NPC / Create Enemy and Adjust NPC / Adjust Enemy movement modes, AI types, AI targets, behaviour flags, and zone-related flags.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,0,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,4,0,4">
        Movement Modes
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Movement controls how the NPC moves after it spawns. These same movement-style settings are
        also useful when working with <Bold>Adjust NPC / Adjust Enemy</Bold>, because Adjust NPC can
        be used to change an existing NPC’s movement later in the mission.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_npc_movement_settings.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Stand Still</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">The NPC does not move.</Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Patrol Waypoints In Order</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        The NPC patrols each subsequent <Bold>Simple Waypoint</Bold> Event Point within the same
        colour and letter group, following numerical order.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Patrol Waypoints Randomly</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Similar to ordered patrol, but the NPC chooses waypoint Event Points in a random order
        rather than numerical order.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Wander</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        The NPC wanders around the map aimlessly, similar to civilians. The NPC should avoid
        No Wander Zones.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Follow</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        The NPC follows the Event Point specified in the <Bold>Follow EP</Bold> box. For example,
        if the player is Event Point 1, entering 1 makes the NPC follow the player.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Warm Hands</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">Appears unused, but was likely intended for a character warming their hands near a fire.</Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Follow On See</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Similar to Follow, but only activates once the Event Point specified in Follow EP is within
        the NPC’s visual distance.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Hands Up</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        The character has their hands in the air. This appears to work only when the AI Type is not
        None, and only works properly with certain AI types such as Civilian or Cop. Enemy types can
        raise their hands but may still target the player when they see them.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Tied Up</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Was likely intended to be distinct from Hands Up, but appears to behave the same: the
        character has their hands up.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        AI Types
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        AI Type controls the character’s high-level behaviour. This is separate from movement. For
        example, an NPC may stand still but still behave as a hostile enemy when the player comes
        into view.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_npc_ai_type_settings.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Civilian</Bold> — the NPC behaves as an innocent civilian.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Cop</Bold> — targets enemies that attack you. Only cops can arrest.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Violent Youth</Bold> — actively targets the player if they see you.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Guard a Door</Bold> — likely legacy door-guarding behaviour; no obvious current effect.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Driver</Bold> — enters the nearest available vehicle.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Bomb Disposer</Bold> — appears unused.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Biker</Bold> — appears unused.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Fight Test Dummy</Bold> — tutorial fight dummy behaviour, used with combat ability settings.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Bully</Bold> — actively targets the player.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Cop Driver</Bold> — similar to Driver, but for police vehicles only.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Suicide</Bold> — immediately dies on spawn.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Flee Player</Bold> — flees once the player is in sight.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Group Genocide</Bold> — appears unused.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>MIB</Bold> — attacks the player on sight.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Summoner</Bold> — white orb appears around the NPC and they float upward; likely beta Bane-related behaviour.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Hypochondriac</Bold> — alive but passed out.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Shoot Dead Assassin</Bold> — if armed, targets the Guard EP with unlimited fire until the target is dead, then wanders.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        AI Target Fields
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Some AI behaviours use Event Point references. These references must point to the correct
        Event Point number or the behaviour will not affect the intended target.
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Guard EP</Bold> — used for targeting or guard-related behaviour.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Follow EP</Bold> — used by Follow and Follow On See movement modes.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Target EP</Bold> — required by Adjust NPC / Adjust Enemy. This must be the Event Point number of the existing NPC being modified.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#4A2424" BorderBrush="#C45A5A" BorderThickness="2"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="14">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#FFD0D0" FontSize="15">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Target EP warning:</Run>
                <Run>
                    For Adjust NPC / Adjust Enemy, Target EP must correspond to the NPC’s Event Point number.
                    It is the target NPC, not the Adjust NPC event’s own number.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        NPC Behaviour Flags
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Behaviour flags modify how the NPC behaves. Some are straightforward, while others appear to
        be legacy, special-case, or not fully confirmed. These flags may be set when creating the NPC
        or adjusted later using Adjust NPC / Adjust Enemy.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_npc_flags_panel.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Lazy — Bit 0</Bold> — makes the enemy less alert or reactive.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Diligent — Bit 1</Bold> — opposite of Lazy; more alert or persistent. Original string is misspelled as Dilligent.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Gang — Bit 2</Bold> — marks the person as part of a gang or faction.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Fight Back — Bit 3</Bold> — allows the person to fight back when attacked.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Just Kill Player — Bit 4</Bold> — forces hostile intent toward the player specifically.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Robotic — Bit 5</Bold> — makes behaviour more scripted or rigid.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Restricted Movement — Bit 6</Bold> — limits movement, probably within an area, route, or navigation zone.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Only Player Kills — Bit 7</Bold> — only player kills count or are allowed for the NPC.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Blue Zone — Bit 8</Bold> — zone-related flag.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Cyan Zone — Bit 9</Bold> — zone-related flag.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Yellow Zone — Bit 10</Bold> — zone-related flag.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Magenta Zone — Bit 11</Bold> — zone-related flag.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Invulnerable — Bit 12</Bold> — prevents lethal damage.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Guilty — Bit 13</Bold> — marks the person as guilty or criminal.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Fake Wander — Bit 14</Bold> — makes the person appear to wander using simplified/faked wandering.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Can Carry — Bit 15</Bold> — allows the person to be carried.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>
</FlowDocument>
